[{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Phase-Space","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"For systems of Bose particles, the most important states are coherent states. These states allow representation of a large class of dynamical quantum evolution in terms of equivalent stochastic processes.","title":"Phase Space"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Fock-states","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"Coherent states may be represented in terms of Fock states. For a single mode, these are just eigenstates of the number operator a^dagger a, satisfying\n\na^dagger anrangle = nnrangle\n\nand these states are orthonormal langle nmrangle = delta_nm.","title":"Fock states"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Coherent-states","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"Coherent states play a central role in quantum phase space methods, providing a mapping of many-body boson dynamics to equivalent stochastic differential equations.\n\nFor a single bosonic mode, with creation and destruction operators a^dagger, and a, with commutator aa^dagger=1, the coherent states are eigenstates of the annihilation operator\n\naalpharangle =alphaalpharangle\n\nwhere alphain mathbbC can vary over the complex plane and plays the role of a classical amplitude.\n\nIn terms of Fock states, the coherent states take the form\n\nalpharangle = e^-alpha^22sum_n=0^infty fracalpha^nsqrtnnrangle\n\nThese states are overcomplete, with resolution of the identity\n\nmathbb1 = frac1piint d^2alpha alpharanglelanglealpha\n\nThis property is responsible for much of the practical utility of coherent states, furnishing a mapping from quantum operators in Hilbert space to differential operators in phase space.","title":"Coherent states"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Glauber-Sudarshan-P-representation","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"One of the most well-known representations is the Glauber-Sudarshan P-representation (for brevity here called the Glauber-P). For a single mode optical field, the representation of the density matrix is given by\n\nrho = int d^2alpha alpharanglelanglealphaP(alphaalpha^*)\n\nwhere the integral is taken over the entire complex plane. The Glauber-P representation occurs in a single complex variable phase space, as seen from the expansion over diagonal coherent state projectors.\n\nIn the P-representation a coherent state may be sampled as a single point on the complex plane\n\nN = 10000\nstate = Coherent(12.0)\nα,α⁺ = glauberP(state,N)\n\nIn any other distribution the coherent state is more interesting to sample.\n\nNote here that alpha and alpha^+ are simple complex conjugates. In any of the doubled-phase space representations such as the Positive-P representation, they are independent variables.","title":"Glauber-Sudarshan P-representation"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Husimi-Q-representation","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"The Husimi-Q representation has the advantage that it always exists as a non-singular distribution, and is always non-negative. It is defined as the diagonal matrix element of the density matrix in the coherent state basis\n\nQ(alphaalpha^*)=frac1pilangle alpharhoalpharangle\n\nMany of its properties are very direct to prove. For example, moments of Q generate anti-normally ordered operator averages:\n\nint d^2alpha(alpha^*)^palpha^qQ(alphaalpha^*)=langle a^q (a^dag)^qrangle\n\nas may be shown using properties of the trace.\n\nIn this code we make frequent use of the Q function to sample other distributions. In particular, we use the fact that PWQ generate operator averages that are normally ordered, symmetrically ordered, and anti-normally ordered respectively. This may also be expressed in the form of a convolution relationship between distributions, where W and Q are convolutionally broadened relative to the narrower P distribution.\n\nIn the next section we outline the main application of this relationship, which is sampling particular +P distributions for states where a Q function may be easily sampled. ","title":"Husimi-Q representation"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Positive-P-representation","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"In the Positive-P representation the simples way to sample the state is again as a point on the complex plane\n\nα,α⁺ = positiveP(state,N)\n\nHere αα are no longer in general complex conjugates. Even if they are initial conjugates, we emphasize that this is no longer the case in subsequent dynamical evolution of the ensemble of phase space points. Furthermore, unlike the Glauber-P distribution, the +P distribution for a particular quantum state is not unique.\n\nIn this package we primarily focus on single mode problems, taking the general approach of sampling the Husimi-Q funcion, and then exploiting a simple convolutional relationship between the Husimi-Q and a particular choice of +P representation.\n\nA particular choice of +P that can be made for any single mode density matrix is given by\n\nP(alphaalpha^+) = frac14pi^2langle (alpha+(alpha^+)^*)2rho(alpha+(alpha^+)^*)2rangle e^-alpha-(alpha^+)^*^24\n\nWe can then use the transformation\n\nmu = (alpha+(alpha^+)^*)2quadquadgamma = (alpha-(alpha^+)^*)2\n\nwith inverse\n\nalpha = mu + gammaquadquad alpha^+ = mu^* - gamma^*\n\nThe problem reduces to that of sampling the  distribution\n\nP(mugamma)=Q(mumu^*)frace^-gamma^2pi\n\nwhere\n\nQ(alphaalpha^*)equiv fraclangle alpharhoalpharanglepi\n\nis the Husimi-Q representation, and the remaining complex Gaussian distribution is readily sampled as\n\ngamma = frac1sqrt2left(eta_1+ieta_2right)\n\nHere eta_j are independent normal random variates with zero mean and unit variance:\n\nlangle eta_j rangle = 0quadquad langle eta_ieta_jrangle =delta_ij\n\nNormally distributed Gaussian variates are sampled using randn().\n\nWe should emphasize that all states with Q function sampling in this package are also available in the +P representation via this approach. To see details of sampling for a given distribution, see src/methods.jl.","title":"Positive-P representation"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Wigner-representation","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"The Wigner function generates symmetrically ordered operator averages from its moments. It is often used due to being well suited for identifying semi-classical approximations. Many of the simpler Wigner functions are well known and straightforward to sample. However, when the W function has negative regions, or oscillates rapidly, sampling can be more challenging. In this package we implement previously developed methods for sampling Fock states, and also develop a new method to sample Fock states in the positive Wigner representation, a doubled-phase space representation that allows the distribution to remain positive everywhere. ","title":"Wigner-representation"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Positive-Wigner-representation","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"Just as the phase space of the P-representation can be doubled to give the positive-P, we can also double the phase space of the W-representation, to give a positive-W representation. The relationship between positive-P and positive-W is a convolution\n\nW_+(alphaalpha^+)=frac2piint d^2lambda e^-2lambda^2P_+(alpha+lambdaalpha^++lambda^*)\n\nWe can make a change of variables to mu gamma, by defining lambda = mu-(alpha+alpha^+)2, and\n\nalpha = mu + gammaquadquad alpha^+ = mu^* - gamma^*\n\nwith inverse\n\nmu = frac12left(alpha+(alpha^+)^*right)quadquad gamma = frac12left(alpha-(alpha^+)^*right)\n\nUsing the specific form of P_+ in terms of the Q function, we have\n\nW_+(alphaalpha^+)=frac2piint d^2mu e^-2mu-(alpha+(alpha^+)^*)2^2frace^-alpha-(alpha^+)^*^244pi^2Q(mumu^*)\n\nWe note that\n\nint d^2alphaint d^2alpha^+ W_+(alphaalpha^+)=int d^2gammaint d^2mu W_+(alphaalpha^+)4\n\nwhere the factor 4 is the Jacobian of the transformation. Hence, we define\n\ntilde W_+(gammamu)equiv 4W_+(alpha(gammamu)alpha^+(gammamu))\n\nand we thus have a particular form for the positive-W of any single mode bosonic quantum state\n\ntilde W_+(gammamu) = frace^-gamma^2pifrac2pi^2int d^2mu e^-2mu-mu^2Q(mumu^*)\n\ntogether with the inverse given above\n\nW_+(alphaalpha^+)=frac14tilde W_+(gamma(alphaalpha^+)mu(alphaalpha^+))","title":"Positive Wigner representation"},{"category":"section","location":"phasespace/#Fock-state-in-positive-W","page":"Introduction to Phase Space","text":"Using the Q-representation for the Fock state rho = nrangle langle n, and polar coordinates mu=rho e^iphi, mu=r e^itheta, we can carry out the convolution\n\nfrac2pi^2int d^2mue^-2mu^2-2mu^2+2(mumu^*+mu^*mu)fracmu^2ne^-mu^2n\n=\nfrac2pi^2frace^-2mu^2nint_0^infty dr r^2n+1e^-3r^2underbraceint_0^2pidtheta e^4rrhocos(theta-phi)_2pi I_0(4rrho)\n\nUsing the relation between Laguerre polynomials and Bessel function\n\nint_0^infty dr r^2n+1e^-3r^2I_0(4rrho)=frac12fracn3^n+1L_-(n+1)(4rho^23)\n\nand the identity L_-n(x)=e^xL_n-1(-x), we arrive at\n\ntilde W_+(gammamu) = frace^-gamma^2pifrac2e^-2mu^23pi 3^n+1L_n(-4mu^23)\n\nThe gamma distribution is easily sampled. For the distribution of muin mathbbC, as it only depends on muin 0infty), we can sample it via the correctly normalized distribution for mu=x\n\nP_mu(x)=frac4 x e^-2x^233^n+1L_n(-4x^23)\n\nsuch that int_0^infty dx P_mu(x)=1,  and then apply a uniformly sampled random phase theta in 02pi) to construct samples on the complex plane\n\nmu = x e^itheta","title":"Fock state in positive-W"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#Solving-SDEs","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"Solving SDEs"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#Noises","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"Noises"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#randnc","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"randnc"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#realnoise","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"realnoise"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#realbridge","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"realbridge"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#Complex-noise-example","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"Complex noise example"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#Real-noise-example","page":"Solving SDES","text":"","title":"Real noise example"},{"category":"section","location":"sdes/#Recovering-normal-order-from-Wigner-ensemble-averages","page":"Solving SDES","text":"A common approach to quantum phase space simulations involves performing truncated Wigner simulations, allowing symmetrically ordered operator averages. However, in experiments, the physically measurable moments are usually those in normal order. We can recover normal order for an operator average of a given degree if we have access to all symmetrically ordered operator averages up to the same degree.\n\nOne can derive the following useful relationship between normal- and symmetrically-ordered operator averages\n\nlangle (a^dagger)^p a^qrangle = sum_n=0^textrmmin(pq)frac(-1)^nn2^nbinompnbinomqnlangle (a^dagger)^p-na^q-n_textrmsymrangle\n\nThe relationship between normal ordered operator averages and ensemble averages of Wigner trajectories, denoted by overlineleft(dotsright)_W is\n\nlangle (a^dagger)^p a^qrangle = sum_n=0^textrmmin(pq)frac(-1)^nn2^nbinompnbinomqnoverlineleft((alpha^*)^p-nalpha^q-nright)_W","title":"Recovering normal order from Wigner ensemble averages"},{"category":"function","location":"sdes/#PhaseSpaceTools.randnc","page":"Solving SDES","text":"a = randnc(N...)\n\nReturn an array of dimension length(N), containing samples of complex random variables with mean zero and variance one:\n\na^2 = 1 a^2 = (a^*) ^2 = 0\n\nUseful for creating a range of noises that show up in phase-space simulations.\n\nUsage:\n\na = randnc(10) returns a 10-element Array{Complex{Float64},1}.\n\na = randnc(50,100) returns a 50x100-element Array{Complex{Float64},2}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.randnc"},{"category":"function","location":"sdes/#PhaseSpaceTools.realnoise","page":"Solving SDES","text":"Complex variable SDE's in DifferentialEquations.jl have complex noises by default dispatch on complex fields. This method defines a real noise for use with the library.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.realnoise"},{"category":"function","location":"sdes/#PhaseSpaceTools.realbridge","page":"Solving SDES","text":"Complex variable SDE's in DifferentialEquations.jl have complex noises by default dispatch on complex fields. This method defines a real brownian bridge for use with the library.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.realbridge"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Distributions","page":"Distributions","text":"The phase-space distributions that may be sampled for these quantum states are","title":"Distributions"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Husimi-Q","page":"Distributions","text":"","title":"Husimi-Q"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Glauber-P","page":"Distributions","text":"","title":"Glauber-P"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Positive-P","page":"Distributions","text":"","title":"Positive-P"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Wigner","page":"Distributions","text":"","title":"Wigner"},{"category":"section","location":"distributions/#Positive-W","page":"Distributions","text":"","title":"Positive-W"},{"category":"function","location":"distributions/#PhaseSpaceTools.husimiQ","page":"Distributions","text":"α,ᾱ = husimiQ(state <: State,N)\n\nGenerate N samples from the Husimi-Q phase-space distribution for state.\n\nMoments of the Husimi-Q distribution generate quantum operator averages that are anti-normally ordered.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.husimiQ"},{"category":"function","location":"distributions/#PhaseSpaceTools.glauberP","page":"Distributions","text":"α,α⁺ = glauberP(state <: State,N)\n\nGenerate N samples from the Glauber-Sudarshan-P phase-space distribution for state.\n\nMoments of the Glauber-Sudarshan-P distribution generate quantum operator averages that are normally ordered.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.glauberP"},{"category":"function","location":"distributions/#PhaseSpaceTools.positiveP","page":"Distributions","text":"α,α⁺ = positiveP(state <: State,N)\n\nGenerate N samples from the positive-P (+P) phase-space distribution for state.\n\nMoments of the +P distribution generate quantum operator averages that are normally ordered.\n\nIn general the two random variates α,α⁺ are statistically independent for the +P distribution. \n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.positiveP"},{"category":"function","location":"distributions/#PhaseSpaceTools.wigner","page":"Distributions","text":"α,α⁺ = wigner(state <: State,N)\n\nGenerate N samples from wigner phase-space distribution for state.\n\nMoments of the Wigner distribution generate symmetrically ordered quantum operator averages.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.wigner"},{"category":"function","location":"distributions/#PhaseSpaceTools.positiveW","page":"Distributions","text":"α,α⁺ = positiveW(state <: State,N)\n\nGenerate N samples from the positive-W (+W) phase-space distribution for state.\n\nImplemented states are\n\nFock(N)\n\nThe moments of the +W distribution generate quantum operator averages that are symmmetrically ordered.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.positiveW"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Quantum-states","page":"Quantum States","text":"Quantum states available in PhaseSpaceTools.jl are","title":"Quantum states"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Coherent","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Coherent"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Fock","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Fock"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Crescent","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Crescent"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Squeezed","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Squeezed"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#SqueezedTwoMode","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"SqueezedTwoMode"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Thermal","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Thermal"},{"category":"section","location":"states/#Bogoliubov","page":"Quantum States","text":"","title":"Bogoliubov"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Coherent","page":"Quantum States","text":"Coherent(β)\n\nCreate a coherent state with complex amplitude β ∈ ℂ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Coherent"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Fock","page":"Quantum States","text":"Fock(n)\n\nCreate a Fock state for particle number n ∈ ℕ₀.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Fock"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Crescent","page":"Quantum States","text":"Crescent(β,ϵ,q)\n\nCreate a Crescent state with parameters β, ϵ, q.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Crescent"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Squeezed","page":"Quantum States","text":"Squeezed(β,ϵ)\n\nCreate a Squeezed state with parameters β, ϵ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Squeezed"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.SqueezedTwoMode","page":"Quantum States","text":"SqueezedTwoMode(r,ϕ)\n\nCreate a two-mode squeezed state with parameters r, ϕ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.SqueezedTwoMode"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Thermal","page":"Quantum States","text":"Thermal(β,n̄)\n\nCreate a Thermal state with parameters β, n̄.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Thermal"},{"category":"type","location":"states/#PhaseSpaceTools.Bogoliubov","page":"Quantum States","text":"Bogoliubov(u,v,n̄)\n\nCreate a Bogoliubov state with parameters u, v, n̄.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"PhaseSpaceTools.Bogoliubov"},{"category":"section","location":"#Overview","page":"Overview","text":"This package provides sampling methods for commonly used quantum states in various quantum phase-space representations. These include Glauber-Sudarshan-P, Positive-P, Husimi-Q, and Wigner representations.\n\nIt also provides helpers for sampling complex and real noises used in phase-space simulations, including SDE workflows with DifferentialEquations.jl.","title":"Overview"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Overview","text":"In the julia REPL\n\njulia> ]add PhaseSpaceTools\n\njulia> ]test PhaseSpaceTools","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Reference","page":"Overview","text":"If you find this package useful, please cite\n\nM. K. Olsen, A. S. Bradley, Numerical representation of quantum states in the positive-P and Wigner representations, Optics Communications 282, 3924-3929 (2009).\n\nA full erratum is given in this SciPost Commentary.","title":"Reference"}]
